</FONT><B><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE=4><P>Exponential Functions</P>
</B></FONT><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE=2>

</B><P>An exponential function takes the general form </P>

<P ALIGN="CENTER">y = a<SUP>x</SUP> &#9;&#9;(a &gt; 0)</P>
<P ALIGN="CENTER"></P>
<P>The number <B>a</B> is called the <B>base</B> and the number <B>x</B> is called the <B>exponent</B> or index.</P>

<P>Examples of exponential functions:</P>

<P ALIGN="CENTER">y= 2<SUP>x</SUP> (an exponential function with base 2)</P>
<P ALIGN="CENTER">y = 5<SUP>t</SUP> (an exponential function with base 5)</P>
<P ALIGN="CENTER"></P>
<P>These functions are often written in functional notation as:</P>

<P ALIGN="CENTER">f(x) = 2<SUP>x</P>
</SUP><P ALIGN="CENTER">g(t) = 5<SUP>t</P>
</SUP>
<P>Sometimes the quantity a<SUP>x</SUP> may be multiplied by a constant k, say, giving the form:</P>

<P ALIGN="CENTER">y = ka<SUP>x</P>
</SUP>

<P>&nbsp;</P>
</FONT><B><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE=4>Exponential Graphs</P>
</B></FONT><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE=2>

<P>Refer to your lecture notes page 22 for the graphs of y = 2<SUP>x</SUP> and y = 3<SUP>x</SUP>.</P>

<P>&nbsp;</P>
</FONT><B><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE=4>Applications of Exponential Relationships</P>
</B></FONT><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE=2>

